{"key":"processedPost-13977915","value":{"id":13977915,"first":13973048,"last":13977919,"when":1297956337,"utime":"02/17/11 05:25 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>Doc_T said:</b><br />Differently put: if you have mold on one side of a block of cheese, would you cut it off and eat the rest?<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Yes, of course.&nbsp; I cut mold off cheese every day, as do the dairies which make it.&nbsp; <br /><br />However, mold permeates mushroom substrates much more thoroughly than it does cheese, where it remains on the surface and can easily be cut off.&nbsp; When a mushroom substrate contaminates with mold, toss it out.&nbsp; It's not because the mold is poison to us, which it isn't; it's because the mold is toxic to our mushroom mycelium and the mold spores contaminate our growing areas, making future grows much more difficult.<br />RR","title":"Re: Poisonous Contaminations"}}